  "signature": "ed25519:b2c3d4e5f6a7b8c9d0e1f2a3b4c5d6e7f8a9b0c1d2e3f4a5b6c7d8e9f0a1b2c3",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver must hold ISO 9001 certification or equivalent FDA-recognized quality management system documentation; all code changes tracked in a validated version control system with audit trail; regression test suite coverage above 90% for hemolysis-relevant solver modules.",
      "rationale": "At MRL 5 for a Class III device, software quality assurance requires Gradation 4 compliance. The CFD solver holds ISO 9001 certification and maintains a validated version control system, but regression test suite coverage for hemolysis-specific modules reached only 78%, falling short of the 90% threshold. Achieved level 3 reflects partial compliance with the structured QA requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Order-of-accuracy verification must be demonstrated for all governing equations using manufactured solutions; verification must cover hemolysis transport scalar and turbulence closure; results documented in a peer-reviewed verification report.",
      "rationale": "Code verification via method of manufactured solutions was completed for the Navier-Stokes and turbulence equations, confirming expected second-order spatial accuracy. However, the hemolysis scalar transport equation was not subjected to manufactured-solution verification, limiting the achieved level to 3. A Gradation 4 rating requires full coverage of all active physics including the power-law hemolysis model."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Richardson extrapolation or GCI analysis must be performed on at least three systematically refined meshes; discretization error in hemolysis index must be bounded below 5% of the mean predicted value; near-wall mesh quality (y+ < 5) must be demonstrated across all operating points.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was conducted with GCI analysis. The coarsest mesh yielded a GCI of 8.2% on the hemolysis index, exceeding the 5% bound required for Gradation 4. The two finer meshes satisfied the criterion, but the assessment protocol requires all meshes in the refinement sequence to meet the bound. Near-wall y+ targets were satisfied. Achieved level 3 is assigned."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions must match COU operating envelope within ±5% for flow rate and rotational speed; blood analogue fluid rheology must be characterised and reported; all five COU flow-speed combinations must be represented in the validation dataset.",
      "rationale": "All five COU flow-speed combinations were reproduced in the validation experiment using a porcine blood analogue with characterised rheology. Flow rate and rotational speed matched COU targets within ±3.1% and ±1.8% respectively. Test condition fidelity satisfies Gradation 4 requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (e.g., normalised RMS error or validation metric U_val) must be computed with uncertainty bounds; comparison must account for both experimental and simulation uncertainty; metric must be below the decision-relevant threshold established in the COU.",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison was performed using a normalised RMS error metric. The metric value of 0.19 exceeded the COU threshold of 0.15 at two of the five operating points. Experimental uncertainty was propagated but simulation uncertainty from the Monte Carlo UQ was not fully integrated into the comparison metric, preventing a Gradation 4 rating."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The primary QoI (normalised index of hemolysis, NIH) must be directly measured in validation experiments; secondary QoIs (shear stress distribution, residence time) must be reported; QoI definitions must be consistent between simulation and experiment.",
      "rationale": "The normalised index of hemolysis was directly measured in all validation experiments using a spectrophotometric plasma-free haemoglobin assay. Shear stress distributions were characterised via micro-PIV at two operating points. QoI definitions are consistent between the CFD post-processing routines and the experimental measurement protocol. Gradation 4 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "At MRL 5 for a Class III VAD, the highest gradation (5) is required for validation relevance. The validation experiments were conducted on the FDA generic pump geometry, which closely approximates the target device but is not identical to the commercial VAD impeller. Operating conditions covered the clinical envelope but used a porcine blood analogue rather than human blood. These geometry and fluid differences reduce relevance. The assessment team determined that the achieved level is 3, reflecting moderate relevance. A Gradation 5 rating would require patient-equivalent fluid and device-identical geometry validation, which was not feasible within the study timeline. The rationale for requiring Gradation 5 is discussed narratively here, but no structured acceptanceCriteria record was filed at the time of assessment."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence must be demonstrated to at least four orders of magnitude residual reduction for all transported quantities; round-off error analysis must confirm double-precision arithmetic is sufficient; solver error must be shown to be negligible relative to discretization error.",
      "rationale": "Iterative residuals for all equations converged to five orders of magnitude reduction. Double-precision arithmetic was confirmed throughout. Solver error was estimated at less than 0.3% of the discretization error budget, satisfying Gradation 3 requirements. No gap identified for this factor."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "A formal user qualification procedure must be documented; simulation setup must be reviewed by a second qualified analyst; boundary condition application must be traceable to the COU specification document.",
      "rationale": "The simulation setup was performed by a single analyst without independent second-analyst review, which is required for Gradation 3. Boundary conditions were traceable to the COU specification, and the analyst holds relevant CFD credentials. The absence of independent review limits the achieved level to 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The hemolysis constitutive model must be selected based on a documented comparative assessment of at least three candidate models; model selection rationale must reference published validation data for rotating blood-contacting devices; sensitivity of hemolysis index to model form must be quantified.",
      "rationale": "The power-law Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis model was selected without a formal comparative assessment against alternative models (e.g., Taskin, Arora). Published literature supports its use in centrifugal pumps, but no sensitivity analysis was conducted to quantify model-form uncertainty on the hemolysis index. This limits the achieved level to 2, well below the required Gradation 4."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model input parameters must have documented sources with traceability to measurement data; uncertainty distributions must be assigned to all sensitive inputs identified by sensitivity analysis; Monte Carlo propagation must cover at least 10,000 samples.",
      "rationale": "Sensitivity analysis identified six influential input parameters including fluid viscosity, power-law exponents, and inlet velocity profile. Uncertainty distributions were assigned to five of the six parameters; the power-law stress exponent distribution was assumed Gaussian without direct measurement support. Monte Carlo propagation used 15,000 samples. Partial input characterisation limits the achieved level to 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "At least three independent experimental replicates must be performed at each operating point; inter-replicate variability must be reported as a coefficient of variation; sample preparation and handling procedures must be documented to ISO 10993 standards.",
      "rationale": "Two experimental replicates were performed at each of the five operating points. Gradation 3 requires a minimum of three independent replicates. Inter-replicate variability (CV 4–9%) was reported. Sample handling followed internal laboratory protocols rather than ISO 10993, introducing additional uncertainty. Achieved level 2 is assigned."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Equivalency between validation experiment inputs and COU inputs must be demonstrated for all primary boundary conditions; any differences must be quantified and their impact on QoI assessed via sensitivity analysis; fluid property equivalency must be established through rheological characterisation.",
      "rationale": "Rheological characterisation confirmed that the porcine blood analogue matched human blood viscosity within 6% across the shear rate range of interest. Inlet velocity profiles were matched to within ±4% of the COU specification. However, the rotational speed equivalency at the highest operating point differed by 7.3%, exceeding the 5% tolerance. Sensitivity analysis was not performed for this specific deviation, limiting the achieved level to 3."
    }
  ],
